>    Kolja did not have effective control of more than three Voting
>    Tokens at the time Proposals 3829-3830 were distributed, because he
>    had granted Power of Attorney to Steve.

>Decision of Board:   OVERTURN/FALSE

Completing the process for this appeal seems a bit tricky to me.  It's not
clear to me what it actually means to vacate an order to vacate a PO which
was already satisfied.  We've had a previous discussion on whether vacating
an order does anything to reverse collateral (secondary) effects of an order
that have occurred prior to the vacation.  IIRC, we decided that it could not
(and that is my opinion, as well).  This means that vacating the vacation of
a satisfied PO would have no affect on the condition of the PO, i.e. it would
continue to be satisfied.  One might argue that since such a vacate order
caused a reversal PO to be issued,  the reversal PO is also vacated.  But
this reversal PO is only a collateral effect of the original vacation, and
IMO, the reversal PO would not be automatically vacated.

However, I think R1807 gives me an out:

Rule 1807/0 (Power=1)
Validity of Appellate Orders

      Since Appellate Orders cannot be appealed, Appellate Orders are
      valid only if addressed to:
        a) The Clerk of the Courts in eir Official capacity;
        ...

So, with the consent of one or more of my fellow justices, I issue
the following Appellate Orders to Steve in eir Official capacity
as Clerk of the Courts:

1)  The CotC is hereby commanded to issue a Payment Order for 1 VT
    naming Kolja as the Payor and the Bank as Payee.
2)  The CotC is hereby commanded to issue a Payment Order for 1 Indulgence
    naming Kolja as the Payor and the Bank as Payee.

These orders will have the effect of reinstating the Failure to Vote
penalties which should apply to Kolja based on this Appeal.

